Was excited to try the 5 course tasting menu with my girlfriend but extremely disappointed to say that it was very sub par and not worth the bill. I would be hesitant to pay $150 for the meal never mind double that. 1. The mushroom soup given in the beginning was tasty but cold. 2. The four oyster with caviar dish was too creamy and nothing special. 3. The salmon dish was by far the worst dish and the coleslaw they put it in on was way too vinegary and reminiscent of KFC coleslaw 4. The steak was fine but once again nothing special. 5. The cheese platter is a laughable excuse for a "course" and no one near me finished. 6. The desert was some sort of chocolate cake mousse that you could get at any fast casual restaurant Overall, very overrated and do not recommend spending your money here when there are so many alternatives for a way better price point.

Best bang for your buck. I love that you can choose how many courses you want and which courses. Yes if you want 5 desserts go ahead, 5 entrees, why not? My top favorites are the seared foie! It can be in top of a fried boot and I will still eat it. The risotto is warm and welcoming, the duck was ok, scallops is another item to not be missed. Definitely order the pineapple flambè it is worth it we were the suckers that passed on it while the table next to us got the show. I will definitely come here again

Decided to dine alone and had an amazing time from time of entry until the moment I left. I did not drink anything but bottled still water with my 5 course meal as I find alcohol interferes with my sense of smell and flavour palate. The service is impeccable and setting, is dimly lit. Upon arrival, they explained the menu and I mentioned it was my first time in SanFran and at their resto along with my lactose issue. After ordering, they offered me a slice of cucumber with black caviar and smoked salmon that i devoured in 2 bites plus a palate pleaser of 2tbsp of broth that was light and flavourful. Next was a chewy crusty bread with a fruity olive oil followed by 5 courses. 1- risotto with dungeness crab; served very hot and creamy. Rice was perfect and upheld the flavour of the sea. A new set of cutlery with each course is a lovely touch along with the napkin placed over my lap - they aim to please! 2- ahi tuna with nori, avocado and enoki mushroom was very fresh with a lovely soy citrus flavour. I found the pace between courses quick but not rushed. I casually sat to enjoy each of my well sized portions. 3- sea bass was perfectly cooked with a light crust and tasty purée; deelish but not sure I'd want a whole plate of it as a main. 4- duck breast is huge!!! I'm nearly full and still have a dessert; got 3/4 way through. Best part was the pulled duck and potato cake that was like a hash patty with a crispy grilled crust- simply fantastic in every way! The duck breast was perfectly cooked and tender. 5- my final course was passion fruit, peach and blackberry sorbet. One scoop of each; each scoop served with a dif cookie. Chocolate crinkle was the best. Flavours are intense but blackberry stood out for me. I only had 1 spoonful of each sorbet as I was stuffed. Just when I thought it was over, a sampler platter of bite sized dessert arrives! I was a trooper and tried one of each. Berry jello, dark chocolate tart, lemon tart and an almond cookie that was phenomenal. There is nothing I disliked or would not happily eat again. I fully understand why people rave about this place as offering a consistent, attentive and classy experience! After paying, they already had my jacket ready at the door to help me put it on. As previous Yelpers noted, I also received a parting gift which I'll open tomorrow at breakfast. I wish I could give this 5+ stars or downgrade all my other Yelp scores but this place is truly in a class of its own.

I made sure to set a reminder to make a reminder to make a reservation 2 months in advanced for the boyfriend's birthday. Easily done on OpenTable, but I think if you call, you'd have a better time slot. We got a 5:30 Saturday reservation which is pretty early for dinner service, but luckily we had a busy day and 530 was perfect for us. Parking was a nightmare, but the sweet staff was understanding when I called and let them know we were running late. They have a $20 valet, but I didn't have any cash on me, so we scoured around until we finally scored a spot nearly 20mins later! We chose to do the 5 course and the 3 course since I felt like 2 servings of cheese and dessert would be too much. We ended up cancelling the cheese course and doing the 4 & 3 course because we were so stuffed! The staff was super understanding and assured us that this normally happens. Their servings are very generous, so try not to eat with your eyes, because your tummy will be crying later. We started with seared foie gras and the seafood risotto. Both were amazing dishes. SO GUUUD. The foie just melts in your mouth. I learned that this was my boyfriend's favorite way of prepared foie. (It's great when meals help couples learn more about each other!) The risotto was so nice and creamy, and not overpowering. The amount of seafood was really generous so you got a bit in every bite. The second course we had the seared scallops and the horseradish crusted salmon. The scallops were nice and big. They had the perfect bite to them and the texture was great. Not over cooked, and just amazing. I really enjoyed the salmon, as the horseradish was not over powering at all. The side slaw was SO GOOD, and had a nice citrus kick to it. I almost didn't share. As I was commenting on how i had loved everything they had brought out so far, in came our 3rd course. I must have completely jinxed myself here. We ordered the seared steak, and the bison. They were cooked medium rare (I asked for rare plus, but not all places do it). Sadly the steak was tasteless as if it had not been seasoned at all. The gnocchi that accompanied it was really nice and chewy. The bison was also not impressive either. Luckily I went from the steak to the bison which was a definite upgrade. The boyfriend who had the bison first which was just mediocre, then had the steak which was even worse. We didn't finish this course as we were totally unsatisfied. It was after this course that we decided we were full and to skip the cheese. We suddenly were not eager to try more dishes, as we were satisfied with the first two. I will come back to try their cheese if I can score a seat at the bar sometime. Jake our server made this recommendation. He was AWESOME! My water glass was never empty, the wine was perfect, and he was just helpful all around. For dessert, the birthday boy chose a tres leches flambe prepared table side. IT WAS GREAT! I basically just ate all the caramel sauce. They were so sweet to bring out a birthday cake as well and some small assortment of sweets. We had a really nice corner table that allowed us a lot of space, but I saw that the other 2 tops were really close to each other. The service is top notch, and the seafood is great. Maybe just stay away from the game meats. The take home pineapple cake was a nice touch. Definitely will be back!

Well, here it is folks! I've been looking for a place to sanctify as "this is where my 'last meal' would take place" if need be and for now, it's the renowned Gary Danko's in San Francisco. It was my husband and I's wedding Anniversary yesterday and we were originally going to splurge on an outing to The French Laundry (booked up) and then we were going to try The Restaurant at the Meadowood, but then we asked ourselves if we really wanted to throw down $800- $1K for our Anniversary dinner? Maybe someday, we thought, but not today! I made us a reservation at Gary Danko's and I'm so glad I did. We didn't drive there, so we didn't deal with parking but as soon as we arrived the lovely gentleman at the door greeted us with a smile and then we were greeted with more smiles inside as we checked in and were asked immediately if we wanted to check any coats. NOTE: We had reservations and I specifically requested a booth or a more quiet table if possible and they so kindly obliged with a romantic corner booth. I appreciate when restaurants make an effort to accommodate little things that will make their diners happier (like seating preferences and extra bread). What can I say? ONE OF THE BEST MEALS and DINING EXPERIENCES EVER. I mean, it was seriously whimsical. (Even despite the woman a table over whom had a bit too much wine and was reading her date the riot act LOUDLY, the staff handled it very professionally and smoothly - aka- boxed them up and processed their check as quickly as possible). Gary Danko's is the service that Mastros used to give. It's an upscale culinary experience that is sophisticated but less stuffy than Jean George's (NYC). It's experiential dining at its finest where they know we're slapping down the cash to eat there, so they're giving us a little theatre as well. What I LOVE other than the dazzling service is how CUSTOMIZABLE you can make your tasting experience. you can select 3, 4 or 5 courses (4 is not on the menu but you can request it), and you can pick any combination of Appetizers, Mains or Dessert. There are AMPLE selections to choose, so let your merry heart fly free as you curate your perfect meal. STANDOUTS for us: Risotto (appetizer) - Highly Recommend Lobster - Delicious Oysters & Caviar (not something we would've normally picked but it was delicious- expect a small portion see photo. ) Crusted Salmon (my personal favorite) Cheeses- amazing broad selection of Cheeses to pick from (see photo). Stumped? Ask your lovely server for suggestions for a win. Flambé dessert- SO SO INCREDIBLY DELICIOUS! Worth the extra $6! I am going to find something else to celebrate soon so I can return. In fact, use this question as a people filter from now on: "Do you like Gary Danko's?" If they say no, be forewarned to not dine with them or have them over for dinner (or maybe associate period) because chances are, nothing pleases them. Just a thought. Thanks for a great night GD! PS- the bathroom is spotless.

Absolutely worth the $$ to dine at Gary Danko. Fine dining is taken to a whole new level at this San Francisco gem. Take your time and enjoy every morsel of their amazing menu. The service here is top notch. As soon as I put the final bite of bread into my mouth, another appeared on my bread plate. The attention patrons receive here is the best I have ever experienced. Gary Danko isn't just a meal, it's an experience!

Gary - step it up! I might catch some flak from the die-hard fans who have dined there for years, but it simply didn't have any "Wow" factor. That's not to say it was bad, but it did not blow us away. But, there are some gaps that I will detail below. They become more glaring when compared to other fine dining experiences. I think they need to shore up some aspects of the service and modernize others in order to deserve maintaining their Michelin status. That said, no regrets, & I can cross it off my list. Details below. FOOD: The food was pretty average for a fine dining establishment. Out of the 5 courses we got, 1 stood out as outstanding, 1 stood out as bad, and the rest were just about average. Outside of that: 1) The complimentary bread was flat out BAD - cold, sliced, with nothing special. The butter didn't even spread easily. As someone in my party said, "The bread we use for our kids' sandwiches are better" 2) The complimentary soup - a tad too much on the sour/acidic side. I understand the intent of opening with that, but the taste was not good. The 1 outstanding course was the Branzinni. It was crisp and well balanced with the sauce and accompanying vegetables. The 1 bad course was the risotto - grossly undercooked, under-seasoned, lacked proper balance relative to the proteins. The duck, beef, and lobster were all just average. Not bad, but didn't delight me either. This might be heretical to some (sorry!), but honestly, it was not that much better than a chain like Houstons or the joint down the street a bit (Hillstones). SERVICE: In many respects, they TECHNICALLY hit the mark. Professionally dressed staff, offered to check in our coats on arrival, and even accommodated our request to get a table 30 minutes earlier. That's where the positives end though. The issues we encountered from a service standpoint were: 1) We all wore dark outfits - I would have expected to be offered a dark napkin, but instead we got white ones, and guess what? A bunch of lint got caught and was visible. 2) As noted above, the bread was not great, but we were hungry and each of us finished off our first two slices pretty quickly. The bread replacement process was where we were frankly taken aback at how abrupt and hurried...the attendant was just short of tossing the bread on our plates before quickly walking away! 3) When taking our order, I've been accustomed to the "ladies' first" custom at a fine dining venue...and I mean ALL ladies. The waiter did take the order from one woman in our party first, but the other lady (my wife) went last. To exacerbate this, the waiter didn't even walk over to my wife's side and she literally would have to shout to overcome the noise level in the place. Now my wife isn't shy so she shot the waiter a look and he quickly walked over to her, but seems like something he should have been trained to do. 4) As dishes came out, some servers took a minute to explain the dish, what was in it, etc. Some servers did NOT. Other servers just quickly mumbled as if they were in a Guinness Book of World Records competition for world's fastest talker. 5) At the end of the service, we were given breakfast cakes as a parting gift. We asked for a bag and the waitress shot us this disgusted and incredulous look, and asked "You need a bag for that?" First of all, YES, we wanted a bag, so just give us a damn bag and second, many other tables with parties of 2 or 4 had bags as well, with the cakes inside. WTF? In short, the service was below expectations. ATMOSPHERE/AMBIANCE: The place was LOUD. There was definitely one table where a lady was clearly tipsy and going off with some borderline inappropriate comments regarding how "asian women tend to blah blah blah." The staff probably should have stepped in and asked her to politely tone it down. Thankfully her husband shushed her, but jeez. The place was crowded. In my opinion, too many tables for the space and certainly too many tables for the staff to cover with a personal touch. When the staff is literally walking a tightrope to maneuver the cheese cart and banana flambe cart in between tables, and asking folks near the dessert making process to be aware of flames - you have to just cut the number of tables. To reinforce that observation, waiting for the bathroom interfered with the staff's routes from the kitchen to tables. I get having soft lighting for setting the mood, but there is a point where it's simply too dark! When we walked in, it was already a tad too dark, but midway through our dinner, they dimmed the lights even more. VALUE: On the surface, $128 for 5 courses seems very reasonable, but that actually averages out to $25+ per course. By comparison, another fine dining venue has 13 courses for $225 (was $185 a year ago), which is $17+ per, and was $14+ a year ago. I can say the Food, Service, and Ambiance at this other venue is 5 stars across the board.

I'm conflicted. This restaurant is hard to judge. You may have varying experience depending on what you order. However I do agree the the service was pretty good. The atmosphere was classy. I called about 1.5 month in advance to secure a 9:30pm reservation on a Friday. So you can see how popular the restaurant is. We were a party of 4 so we really had a good sample of dishes. What really impressed me were the appetizers! I wish I knew and just ordered all appetizers. Shrimp risotto was awesome! A mix of creamy and tangy with the sweetness of fresh shrimp mixed into the perfect balance of flavor. This was my favorite risotto of all time! Next is the oyster with caviar. Flavor was also well balanced and oyster lightly cooked to perfection! The foie gras was decent and they do give a generous portion but I don't feel this dish was outstanding compared the the foie gras I've tasted in the past. Nothing special. Unfortunately, the rest of the meal was disappointing. I was extremely disappointed at the entrees. Out of the four dishes, only one sort of lived up to expectation. We tried the steak, Maine lobster, quail and duck. The duck was pretty good cook medium rare. Very juicy and with a great texture. But not out of this world. The steak was too dry. My husband just made smoked ribeye for BBQ few days prior to this dinner and everyone agreed his steak was much better! Come on! I expected more from a Michelin restaurant. The lobster wasn't bad but lacking flavor. All I tasted was butter.... The quail was just horrible! Meat lacked freshness and almost tasted spoiled. And I did not like the stuffing. As for dessert, we tried all the soufflé (chocolate and Grand marnier). I say the chocolate soufflé was decent but the grand marnier was super sweet. I couldn't finish it. The lemon soufflé cake was actually the best out of all the desserts and the creme brûlée was worth a try. Overall I was expecting more from Gary Danko and I felt they did not live up to my expectation from reading all the reviews. 3.5 star.

    Decided to dine alone and had an amazing time from time of entry until the moment I left. I did not drink anything but bottled still water with my 5 course meal as I find alcohol interferes with my sense of smell and flavour palate. The service is impeccable and setting, is dimly lit. Upon arrival, they explained the menu and I mentioned it was my first time in SanFran and at their resto along with my lactose issue.

    After ordering, they offered me a slice of cucumber  with black caviar and smoked salmon that i devoured in 2 bites plus a palate pleaser of 2tbsp of broth that was light and flavourful. Next was a chewy crusty bread with a fruity olive oil followed by 5 courses.

    1- risotto with dungeness crab; served very hot and creamy. Rice was perfect and upheld the flavour of the sea. A new set of cutlery with each course is a lovely touch along with the napkin placed over my lap - they aim to please!
    2- ahi tuna with nori, avocado and enoki mushroom was very fresh with a lovely soy citrus flavour.
    I found the pace between courses quick but not rushed. I casually sat to enjoy each of my well sized portions.
    3- sea bass was perfectly cooked with a light crust and tasty purée; deelish but not sure I'd want a whole plate of it as a main.
    4- duck breast is huge!!! I'm nearly full and still have a dessert; got 3/4 way through. Best part was the pulled duck and potato cake that was like a hash patty with a crispy grilled crust- simply fantastic in every way! The duck breast was perfectly cooked and tender.
    5- my final course was passion fruit, peach and blackberry sorbet. One scoop of each; each scoop served with a dif cookie. Chocolate crinkle was the  best. Flavours are intense but blackberry stood out for me. I only had 1 spoonful of each sorbet as I was stuffed.  Just when I thought it was over, a sampler platter of bite sized dessert arrives! I was a trooper and tried one of each. Berry jello, dark chocolate tart, lemon tart and an almond cookie that was phenomenal. There is nothing I disliked or would not happily eat again.

    I fully understand why people rave about this place as offering a consistent, attentive and classy experience! After paying, they already had my jacket ready at the door to help me put it on. As previous Yelpers noted, I also received a parting gift which I'll open tomorrow at breakfast. I wish I could give this 5+ stars or downgrade all my other Yelp scores but this place is truly in a class of its own.

We ended up cancelling the cheese course and doing the 4 & 3 course because we were so stuffed! The staff was super understanding and assured us that this normally happens. Their servings are very generous, so try not to eat with your eyes, because your tummy will be crying later.

    We started with seared foie gras and the seafood risotto. Both were amazing dishes. SO GUUUD. The foie just melts in your mouth. I learned that this was my boyfriend's favorite way of prepared foie. (It's great when meals help couples learn more about each other!) The risotto was so nice and creamy, and not overpowering. The amount of seafood was really generous so you got a bit in every bite.

    The second course we had the seared scallops and the horseradish crusted salmon. The scallops were nice and big. They had the perfect bite to them and the texture was great. Not over cooked, and just amazing. I really enjoyed the salmon, as the horseradish was not over powering at all. The side slaw was SO GOOD, and had a nice citrus kick to it. I almost didn't share.

    As I was commenting on how i had loved everything they had brought out so far, in came our 3rd course. I must have completely jinxed myself here. We ordered the seared steak, and the bison. They were cooked medium rare (I asked for rare plus, but not all places do it). Sadly the steak was tasteless as if it had not been seasoned at all. The gnocchi that accompanied it was really nice and chewy. The bison was also not impressive either. Luckily I went from the steak to the bison which was a definite upgrade. The boyfriend who had the bison first which was just mediocre, then had the steak which was even worse. We didn't finish this course as we were totally unsatisfied.

    It was after this course that we decided we were full and to skip the cheese. We suddenly were not eager to try more dishes, as we were satisfied with the first two. I will come back to try their cheese if I can score a seat at the bar sometime. Jake our server made this recommendation. He was AWESOME! My water glass was never empty, the wine was perfect, and he was just helpful all around.

    For dessert, the birthday boy chose a tres leches flambe prepared table side. IT WAS GREAT! I basically just ate all the caramel sauce. They were so sweet to bring out a birthday cake as well and some small assortment of sweets.

    We had a really nice corner table that allowed us a lot of space, but I saw that the other 2 tops were really close to each other. The service is top notch, and the seafood is great. Maybe just stay away from the game meats. The take home pineapple cake was a nice touch. Definitely will be back!

    Well, here it is folks! I've been looking for a place to sanctify as "this is where my 'last meal' would take place" if need be and for now, it's the renowned Gary Danko's in San Francisco.

    It was my husband and I's wedding Anniversary yesterday and we were originally going to splurge on an outing to The French Laundry (booked up) and then we were going to try The Restaurant at the Meadowood, but then we asked ourselves if we really wanted to throw down $800- $1K for our Anniversary dinner? Maybe someday, we thought, but not today! I made us a reservation at Gary Danko's and I'm so glad I did.

    We didn't drive there, so we didn't deal with parking but as soon as we arrived the lovely gentleman at the door greeted us with a smile and then we were greeted with more smiles inside as we checked in and were asked immediately if we wanted to check any coats.

    NOTE: We had reservations and I specifically requested a booth or a more quiet table if possible and they so kindly obliged with a romantic corner booth. I appreciate when restaurants make an effort to accommodate little things that will make their diners happier (like seating preferences and extra bread).

    What can I say? ONE OF THE BEST MEALS and DINING EXPERIENCES EVER. I mean, it was seriously whimsical. (Even despite the woman a table over whom had a bit too much wine and was reading her date the riot act LOUDLY, the staff handled it very professionally and smoothly - aka- boxed them up and processed their check as quickly as possible). Gary Danko's is the service that  Mastros used to give. It's an upscale culinary experience that is sophisticated but less stuffy than Jean George's (NYC). It's experiential dining at its finest where they know we're slapping down the cash to eat there, so they're giving us a little theatre as well.

    What I LOVE other than the dazzling service is how CUSTOMIZABLE you can make your tasting experience. you can select 3, 4 or 5 courses (4 is not on the menu but you can request it), and you can pick any combination of Appetizers, Mains or Dessert. There are AMPLE selections to choose, so let your merry heart fly free as you curate your perfect meal.

    STANDOUTS for us:

    Risotto (appetizer) - Highly Recommend
    Lobster - Delicious
    Oysters & Caviar (not something we would've normally picked but it was delicious- expect a small portion see photo. )
    Crusted Salmon (my personal favorite)
    Cheeses- amazing broad selection of Cheeses to pick from (see photo). Stumped? Ask your lovely server for suggestions for a win.
    Flambé dessert- SO SO INCREDIBLY DELICIOUS! Worth the extra $6!

    I am going to find something else to celebrate soon so I can return. In fact, use this question as a people filter from now on: "Do you like Gary Danko's?" If they say no, be forewarned to not dine with them or have them over for dinner (or maybe associate period) because chances are, nothing pleases them.

    Just a thought. Thanks for a great night GD!

    PS- the bathroom is spotless.

    5/8/2018

    1 check-in

    Gary - step it up!

    I might catch some flak from the die-hard fans who have dined there for years, but it simply didn't have any "Wow" factor. That's not to say it was bad, but it did not blow us away. But, there are some gaps that I will detail below. They become more glaring when compared to other fine dining experiences.  

    I think they need to shore up some aspects of the service and modernize others in order to deserve maintaining their Michelin status.

    That said, no regrets, & I can cross it off my list.   Details below.

    FOOD:
    The food was pretty average for a fine dining establishment.  Out of the 5 courses we got, 1 stood out as outstanding, 1 stood out as bad, and the rest were just about average.  Outside of that:

    1) The complimentary bread was flat out BAD - cold, sliced, with nothing special.  The butter didn't even spread easily.  As someone in my party said, "The bread we use for our kids' sandwiches are better"

    2) The complimentary soup - a tad too much on the sour/acidic side.  I understand the intent of opening with that, but the taste was not good.

    The 1 outstanding course was the Branzinni.  It was crisp and well balanced with the sauce and accompanying vegetables.  The 1 bad course was the risotto - grossly undercooked, under-seasoned, lacked proper balance relative to the proteins.  The duck, beef, and lobster were all just average.  Not bad, but didn't delight me either.

    This might be heretical to some (sorry!), but honestly, it was not that much better than a chain like Houstons or the joint down the street a bit (Hillstones).

    SERVICE:
    In many respects, they TECHNICALLY hit the mark.  Professionally dressed staff, offered to check in our coats on arrival, and even accommodated our request to get a table 30 minutes earlier.  That's where the positives end though.

    The issues we encountered from a service standpoint were:

    1) We all wore dark outfits - I would have expected to be offered a dark napkin, but instead we got white ones, and guess what? A bunch of lint got caught and was visible.

    2) As noted above, the bread was not great, but we were hungry and each of us finished off our first two slices pretty quickly.  The bread replacement process was where we were frankly taken aback at how abrupt and hurried...the attendant was just short of tossing the bread on our plates before quickly walking away!

    3) When taking our order, I've been accustomed to the "ladies' first" custom at a fine dining venue...and I mean ALL ladies.  The waiter did take the order from one woman in our party first, but the other lady (my wife) went last.  To exacerbate this, the waiter didn't even walk over to my wife's side and she literally would have to shout to overcome the noise level in the place.  Now my wife isn't shy so she shot the waiter a look and he quickly walked over to her, but seems like something he should have been trained to do.

    4) As dishes came out, some servers took a minute to explain the dish, what was in it, etc.  Some servers did NOT.  Other servers just quickly mumbled as if they were in a Guinness Book of World Records competition for world's fastest talker.

    5) At the end of the service, we were given breakfast cakes as a parting gift.  We asked for a bag and the waitress shot us this disgusted and incredulous look, and asked "You need a bag for that?"  First of all, YES, we wanted a bag, so just give us a damn bag and second, many other tables with parties of 2 or 4 had bags as well, with the cakes inside.  WTF?

    In short, the service was below expectations.

    ATMOSPHERE/AMBIANCE:

    The place was LOUD.  There was definitely one table where a lady was clearly tipsy and going off with some borderline inappropriate comments regarding how "asian women tend to blah blah blah."  The staff probably should have stepped in and asked her to politely tone it down.  Thankfully her husband shushed her, but jeez.

    The place was crowded.  In my opinion, too many tables for the space and certainly too many tables for the staff to cover with a personal touch.  When the staff is literally walking a tightrope to maneuver the cheese cart and banana flambe cart in between tables, and asking folks near the dessert making process to be aware of flames - you have to just cut the number of tables.  To reinforce that observation, waiting for the bathroom interfered with the staff's routes from the kitchen to tables.

    I get having soft lighting for setting the mood, but there is a point where it's simply too dark!  When we walked in, it was already a tad too dark, but midway through our dinner, they dimmed the lights even more.

    VALUE:
    On the surface, $128 for 5 courses seems very reasonable, but that actually averages out to $25+ per course.  By comparison, another fine dining venue has 13 courses for $225 (was $185 a year ago),  which is $17+ per,  and was $14+ a year ago.  I can say the Food, Service, and Ambiance at this other venue is 5 stars across the board.

    I'm conflicted. This restaurant is hard to judge. You may have varying experience depending on what you order.

    However I do agree the the service was pretty good. The atmosphere was classy.

    I called about 1.5 month in advance to secure a 9:30pm reservation on a Friday. So you can see how popular the restaurant is. We were a party of 4 so we really had a good sample of dishes.  

    What really impressed me were the appetizers! I wish I knew and just ordered all appetizers.

    Shrimp risotto was awesome! A mix of creamy and tangy with the sweetness of fresh shrimp mixed into the perfect balance of flavor. This was my favorite risotto of all time!

    Next is the oyster with caviar. Flavor was also well balanced and oyster lightly cooked to perfection!

    The foie gras was decent and they do give a generous portion but I don't feel this dish was outstanding compared the the foie gras I've tasted in the past. Nothing special.

    Unfortunately, the rest of the meal was disappointing. I was extremely disappointed at the entrees. Out of the four dishes, only one sort of lived up to expectation.

    We tried the steak, Maine lobster, quail and duck.

    The duck was pretty good cook medium rare. Very juicy and with a great texture. But not out of this world.

    The steak was too dry. My husband just made smoked ribeye for BBQ few days prior to this dinner and everyone agreed his steak was much better! Come on! I expected more from a Michelin restaurant.

    The lobster wasn't bad but lacking flavor. All I tasted was butter....

    The quail was just horrible! Meat lacked freshness and almost tasted spoiled. And I did not like the stuffing.

    As for dessert, we tried all the soufflé (chocolate and Grand marnier). I say the chocolate soufflé was decent but the grand marnier was super sweet. I couldn't finish it.

    The lemon soufflé cake was actually the best out of all the desserts and the creme brûlée was worth a try.

    Overall I was expecting more from Gary Danko and I felt they did not live up to my expectation from reading all the reviews.
